&quot;We see a real strong 21st-century case for nuclear energy.&quot;<br>
<br>
True, they do. But other analysts not in dependent on the industry think the exact opposite is true.<br>
=========================================<br>
<br>
=========================================<br>
&quot;Finland has decided to build a fifth nuclear reactor... Canada decided last year to re-start four power stations which were stopped in 1997.&quot;<br>
1)-<br>
<br>
a) Finland has EXCELLENT alternatives to the new plant. Unfortunately, like the Bermuda Triangle, they are in that eastern Europe swath from the Baltic to the Adriatic where plants are still be built.<br>
<br>
b) Canada - This was the theme of an earlier thread. These are plants where the costs were &quot;stranded&quot; on the public, and private industry got plants for without the crushing capital costs. Even this give-away boondoogle may fail, because British Energy was the biggest investor.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showMessage?topicID=25.topic[quote">pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclea...opic[quote</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->]&lt;!--EZCODE QUOTE START---&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Quote:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;hr&gt;   STRANDED DEBT&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
At the time of its dissolution on April 1, 1999, Ontario Hydro had a debt of $38 billion. Hydro’s nuclear plants were very expensive to build and generated much less revenue than expected due to poor performance, so it was clear that they would not be viable under a fair competitive system. They were thus said to be 'stranded assets’ and the estimated debt that they could not carry was termed 'stranded debt’.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
In the April 1999 accounting, OPG was left with only a $3.4 billion debt to service, and Hydro One, only $4.8 billion. The Stranded Debt was estimated at $21 billion, of which $8 billion will be paid by all electricity consumers through a “Competition Transition Charge”. Ominously, the stranded debt can still be increased, and OPG has since increased its debt.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
By removing most nuclear debt from OPG, the stranded debt allocation has acted as a massive bailout for the nuclear plants, in effect providing a subsidy for nuclear rehabilitation. In particular, the $1.3 billion cost of re-starting the four old Pickering A reactors. In the case of Bruce Power, the elimination of the need to service the multi-billion dollar debt for the Bruce reactors is providing a huge subsidy to a private corporation.&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;!--EZCODE QUOTE END---[/quote]It is also important to note that this does NOT involve NEW plants, just restarts of poorly operating existing plants.<br>
=====================================<br>
